nd acted upon. Important among these influences was the anonymous seventh-century Irish text, On The Twelve Abuses of the Age, a biblically-inspired discussion of the moral duties particular to each sector of society. This volume probes its long influence, and its interaction with the revival of classical ideas. By bringing together scholars of political thought and practice, in lay and religious contexts spanning the seventh to fourteenth centuries, this volume crosses boundaries of periodisation, discipline and approach to reflect upon the medieval evolution of concepts of injustice and means of redress. Contributions address how ideas about justice and injustice were discussed among scholars and theologians, and how those ideas were translated into action through complaint and advice throughout the medieval period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJusticexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJusticexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJusticexSocial aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aJustice, political thought, virtue ethics, religious history, government, middle ages.1 aBreen, Aidan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriggs, Charles F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoyce, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahav, Rina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMews, Constant J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMews, Constant Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNeal, 